David Roberts covers this for
Vox.

19:43.349 --> 19:47.053 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He is a writer and journalist
who has long
reported on the need for
tackling climate

19:47.086 --> 19:48.054 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
change.

19:48.087 --> 19:50.022 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He joins me now from Portland.

19:50.056 --> 19:53.893 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
David Roberts, let's start off
talking about
the man who's going to help the
Trump administration

19:53.926 --> 19:55.294 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
shape energy policy.

19:55.327 --> 19:58.330 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Who is Myron Ebell and what does
he believe?

19:58.364 --> 20:03.803 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID ROBERTS, Vox: Myron Ebell
is the director
of the Climate Change Program at
the Competitive

20:03.836 --> 20:08.174 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Enterprise Institute, which is a
think tank
in Washington, D.C.

20:08.207 --> 20:15.481 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
His belief is that climate
change is a hoax
or possibly no big deal,
happening and no

20:15.514 --> 20:22.555 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
big deal, or possibly happening
and good for
us, depending on which day you
ask him, so

20:22.588 --> 20:25.558 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
certain we don't need any public
policy to
help counter it.

20:25.591 --> 20:31.097 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, in some
ways, he seems
like an ideological fit as far
as what we

20:31.130 --> 20:33.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
understand Donald Trump's
policies to believe
and positions?

20:33.899 --> 20:35.534 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID ROBERTS: That's right.

20:35.568 --> 20:40.973 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think it's a very clear signal
from the
Trump camp that he wasn't
kidding in what

20:41.006 --> 20:42.842 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
he said about climate change on
the trail.

20:42.875 --> 20:45.845 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Let's talk a
little bit
about some of the things the
Trump administration

20:45.878 --> 20:47.646 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
might do.

20:47.680 --> 20:50.983 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
With regards to the Paris
accords -- this
is, for those who are following
along, a whole

20:51.016 --> 20:56.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
group of nations have binded
together to say,
we're going to pledge to cut
emissions going

20:56.489 --> 20:58.257 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
forward.

20:58.290 --> 21:03.329 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If the Trump administration
wanted to, can
they just walk back from those
commitments?

21:03.362 --> 21:05.831 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Can they just walk away from the
accords themselves?

21:05.865 --> 21:08.267 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID ROBERTS: Absolutely.

21:08.300 --> 21:12.271 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The whole premise of the Paris
agreement is
that all the commitments from
all the countries

21:12.304 --> 21:14.406 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
involved are voluntary.

21:14.440 --> 21:18.043 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That was one of the reasons that
it was a
breakthrough is that making
those commitments

21:18.077 --> 21:22.648 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
voluntary sort of opened people,
opened countries
up and made them a little bit
more ambitious.

21:22.681 --> 21:27.586 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the consequence of them
being voluntary
is that Trump can absolutely
walk away.

21:27.620 --> 21:34.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It will take him several years
to formally
get the U.S. out of the accord,
but nothing

21:34.160 --> 21:38.664 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is stopping him from just
stating that he's
not going to pursue the targets
and not going

21:38.697 --> 21:41.934 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to do anything to attempt to
meet our commitments
there.

21:41.967 --> 21:45.037 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And there is no legal mechanism
that can stop
him.

21:45.070 --> 21:48.474 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Same question
with regards
to domestic policy.

21:48.507 --> 21:52.278 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What is a Trump administration
energy policy,
what is that going to look like?

21:52.311 --> 22:00.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID ROBERTS: Well, I think the
first priority
is going to be to dismantle the
Obama environmental

22:00.986 --> 22:02.021 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
legacy.

22:02.054 --> 22:03.923 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That will be the priority.

22:03.956 --> 22:11.297 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, for instance, the Clean
Power Plan, which
is aimed at power plants, will
be either rolled

22:11.330 --> 22:18.971 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
back or delayed or slow-walked
or reversed
entirely, depending on what road
they take.

22:19.004 --> 22:24.476 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think the initial efforts
are all going
to be designed to dismantle
everything that

22:24.510 --> 22:27.079 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Obama has done in this area over
the last
eight years.

22:27.112 --> 22:32.017 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: It's hard to
know if voters
picked Trump because of his
energy policy,

22:32.051 --> 22:35.321 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but I think it's undeniable that
there are
a lot of people in the country,
especially

22:35.354 --> 22:40.259 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in states like West Virginia,
who think that,when
you talk about cutting carbon
emissions, you

22:40.292 --> 22:44.797 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
mean that you're cutting their
jobs, that
energy costs are going to go up.

22:44.830 --> 22:49.702 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And to a lot of voters, that
just doesn't
seem like an exchange they want
to make.

22:49.735 --> 22:54.506 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, that -- in some ways,
Trump has something
of mandate, doesn't he?

22:54.540 --> 22:57.243 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID ROBERTS: I don't think so,
William.

22:57.276 --> 22:58.911 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
A couple of things.

22:58.944 --> 23:03.482 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One is, not a lot of people know
this yet,
but renewable energy now employs
far more

23:03.515 --> 23:06.285 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people in the United States than
coal does,
certainly.

23:06.318 --> 23:10.823 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's more jobs in the solar
industry alone
than there is in coal anymore.

23:10.856 --> 23:17.062 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, in terms of job growth,
renewables are
a much more fertile source of
that than fossil

23:17.096 --> 23:19.064 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
fuels.

23:19.098 --> 23:24.837 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Secondly, if you actually go
beneath the general
level and poll the public on
individual questions

23:24.870 --> 23:30.809 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
like should we do something to
restrain carbon
emissions, should we tighten
regulations on

23:30.843 --> 23:36.448 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
pollution, should we support
renewable energy,
support for those policies is
incredibly high

23:36.482 --> 23:40.986 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
across the board, across
demographics, across
regions of the country.

23:41.020 --> 23:45.624 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you're looking at individual
environmental
policies, public support is
enormous.

23:45.658 --> 23:49.461 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The problem is that there just
aren't that
many members of the public who
make those

23:49.495 --> 23:51.563 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
issues their priority.

23:51.597 --> 23:55.801 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So I don't think that Trump's
win necessarily
tells us anything about what the
public thinks

23:55.834 --> 24:00.105 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about energy policy, so much as
it tells us
that the public just doesn't
think about energy

24:00.139 --> 24:01.940 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
policy very much.

24:01.974 --> 24:05.077 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: With regards
to those coal
jobs, Trump made a repeated
pledge that he's

24:05.110 --> 24:07.112 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
going to bring the coal industry
back.

24:07.146 --> 24:08.981 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Is that in the president's power
to do?

24:09.014 --> 24:10.916 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID ROBERTS: Absolutely not.

24:10.949 --> 24:17.056 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, the main thing that is
killing coal
right now in the U.S. is cheap
natural gas,

24:17.089 --> 24:19.591 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and that's market competition.

24:19.625 --> 24:23.729 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's market competition that's
killing coal,
and that's going to be true no
matter what

24:23.762 --> 24:25.597 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Trump does.

24:25.631 --> 24:29.501 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there's automation in the
coal industry,
so coal mining jobs have been
declining for

24:29.535 --> 24:37.109 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
40 years now from their historic
highs and
will continue to decline as
automation increases.

24:37.142 --> 24:44.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, most of the forces that are
adverse to
coal in the U.S., particularly
adverse to

24:44.416 --> 24:49.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
coal mining jobs, are outside
the president's
control and are definitely going
to continue

24:49.955 --> 24:51.757 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
no matter what Trump does.

24:51.790 --> 24:55.794 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The interesting thing is whether
those people
that he made those promises to
remember those

24:55.828 --> 24:57.696 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
promises and hold him
accountable.

24:57.730 --> 25:00.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Let's say
Trump does everything
that he promised to do, he
treats climate

25:00.966 --> 25:07.005 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
change like a hoax, he walks
away from the
Paris accords, he dismantles the
EPA's regulations.

25:07.039 --> 25:11.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What does the U.S.' position
mean for the
global effort to cut carbon
emissions?

25:11.944 --> 25:15.948 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How much of this will impact
what the rest
of the planet is doing already?

25:15.981 --> 25:21.854 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID ROBERTS: That is indeed
the $6 million
question, and no one quite knows
the answer

25:21.887 --> 25:22.855 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
yet.

25:22.888 --> 25:24.556 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
The news is not good.

25:24.590 --> 25:28.794 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A lot of the Paris agreement and
a lot of
international cooperation on
climate change

25:28.827 --> 25:32.264 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
has been built on U.S.
leadership recently.

25:32.297 --> 25:37.803 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Obama's leadership helped bring
China into
the fold, to the table to do
this.

25:37.836 --> 25:42.608 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then the prospect of the
U.S. and China
acting in concert helped bring
the rest of

25:42.641 --> 25:44.710 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the world to the table.

25:44.743 --> 25:49.481 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, in a large sense, this
edifice is built
on top of U.S. leadership.

25:49.515 --> 25:56.155 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, if you yank U.S. leadership
out from underneath
it, at the very least, I think
it's going

25:56.188 --> 25:59.658 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to be much more shaky and
vulnerable.

25:59.691 --> 26:06.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Whether it continues on as it
has been depends
on a lot of economic forces and
technological

26:06.632 --> 26:09.234 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
innovation and a lot of things
that we can't
really predict.

26:09.268 --> 26:15.874 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think, at the very least,
action is
much more fragile and contingent
than it was

26:15.908 --> 26:17.376 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
before this news.

26:17.409 --> 26:20.879 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
David Roberts
of Vox, thank you very much.

26:20.913 --> 26:28.887 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID ROBERTS: Thank you,
William.

26:28.921 --> 26:37.029 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The so-called
EB-5 visa permits
foreign nationals to invest in
job-creating

26:37.062 --> 26:40.499 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
programs in the U.S. in exchange
for permanent
residency.

26:40.532 --> 26:44.670 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it's been scandal-plagued,
leading to
calls for reform.

26:44.703 --> 26:49.341 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As Congress gets set to tackle
some final
business before the end of this
year, will

26:49.374 --> 26:51.877 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the program finally get fixed?

26:51.910 --> 26:55.180 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Our economics Paul Solman takes
a look.

26:55.214 --> 26:57.349 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's part of his weekly series,
Making Sense.

26:57.382 --> 27:02.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NOREEN IQBAL, Dubai: See, in
Dubai the thing
is, as long as you work in
Dubai, you can

27:03.021 --> 27:04.256 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
live in Dubai.

27:04.289 --> 27:06.892 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But what if you leave the job?

27:06.925 --> 27:09.795 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have to go back to Pakistan,
which we don't
want to.

27:09.828 --> 27:13.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Noreen and Shehryar
Iqbal thought
they had a surefire way to avoid
a return

27:13.999 --> 27:14.967 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to their native Pakistan.

27:15.000 --> 27:16.568 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NOREEN IQBAL: It's not a safe
country.

27:16.602 --> 27:19.404 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SHEHRYAR IQBAL, Dubai: It's got
a lot of security
challenges.

27:19.438 --> 27:22.975 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: He's a flight
attendant for Dubai's
national airline.

27:23.008 --> 27:25.444 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She was, too, until they had
kids.

27:25.477 --> 27:33.085 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Their plan, sock away enough of
their salaries
to buy their way into America
via the EB-5

27:33.118 --> 27:38.190 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
visa program, which grants green
cards, and
eventually U.S. citizenship, to
foreigners

27:38.223 --> 27:40.492 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and their immediate families.

27:40.526 --> 27:46.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just invest half-a-million
dollars to create
at least 10 full-time jobs in
either a rural

27:46.698 --> 27:50.035 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
project or an urban area with a
high unemployment
rate.

27:50.068 --> 27:52.504 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NOREEN IQBAL: We saved even the
allowance
money.

27:52.538 --> 27:54.339 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I can say that.

27:54.373 --> 27:59.111 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's so embarrassing for us to
tell somebody
that allowance money is for you
to eat, but

27:59.144 --> 28:00.546 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
we used to save that also.

28:00.579 --> 28:03.549 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Oh, you mean the
money that the
airline would give you.

28:03.582 --> 28:07.352 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NOREEN IQBAL: The airline give
you on your
flight to have your food and
everything, we

28:07.386 --> 28:08.353 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
would save that also.

28:08.387 --> 28:09.421 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And put it away.

28:09.454 --> 28:11.089 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
NOREEN IQBAL: Put it away.

28:11.123 --> 28:14.259 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: To that, they added
Shehryar's
small inheritance -- his parents
had died

28:14.293 --> 28:19.131 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in a car crash when he was a
teenager -- and
investments they'd made to grow
their nest

28:19.164 --> 28:20.532 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
egg.

28:20.566 --> 28:22.401 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SHEHRYAR IQBAL: She bought a
little studio
in a nice upscale area.

28:22.434 --> 28:23.869 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's called the Jumeirah Lake
Towers.

28:23.902 --> 28:27.439 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was generating a very, very
good rental
income.

28:27.472 --> 28:32.611 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Are you -- you're
starting to
remember it all?

28:32.644 --> 28:33.612 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's what's going on?

28:33.645 --> 28:34.646 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
NOREEN IQBAL: Sorry.

28:34.680 --> 28:36.982 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: No, no, it's OK.

28:37.015 --> 28:41.186 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NOREEN IQBAL: So, we rarely talk
about this,
because I start to...

28:41.219 --> 28:46.258 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: A lot of tears have
been shed
over the EB-5 project the Iqbals
chose to

28:46.291 --> 28:50.862 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
invest in, one we first covered
last year
here on Making Sense.

28:50.896 --> 28:56.935 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Jay Peak ski resort in
Northern Vermont,
coupled with plans for a hugely
ambitious

28:56.969 --> 29:02.608 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
stem cell manufacturing facility
affiliated
with a South Korean biotech
firm.

29:02.641 --> 29:07.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, in April, the Securities
and Exchange
Commission charged developers
Ariel Quiros

29:07.613 --> 29:14.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and Bill Stenger with 52 counts
of federal
securities violations, alleging
they'd misused

29:14.319 --> 29:23.161 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
$200 million of EB-5 investor
funds, running
the ski resort project as a
giant Ponzi scheme,

29:23.195 --> 29:26.665 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and the stem cell project as a
total fraud.

29:26.698 --> 29:31.370 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Iqbals, who put down their
money on stem
cells, have lost not just their
half-million

29:31.403 --> 29:37.242 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
dollar investment, but another
$65,000 in
legal and administrative fees,
with not a

29:37.275 --> 29:39.611 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
green card in sight.

29:39.645 --> 29:44.650 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We talked to them on their
recent visit to
the U.S. on tourist visas using
their free

29:44.683 --> 29:46.418 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
