is that Facebook doesn't make a
lot of data

39:30.868 --> 39:32.670 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
available publicly.

39:32.704 --> 39:38.109 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So the analysis that we did is
just one slice
of a lot of different
investigations that

39:38.142 --> 39:39.844 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think people should be able to
do.

39:39.877 --> 39:42.447 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We don't know the impact of fake
news on the
election.

39:42.480 --> 39:46.351 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I don't think it's correct to
say that it
swayed things in favor of Trump.

39:46.384 --> 39:50.221 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't think it was a deciding
factor, but
it definitely had some kind of a
factor.

39:50.255 --> 39:55.293 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The fact that fake news was
going more viral
towards Election Day than
mainstream news

39:55.326 --> 39:58.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
reporting is really surprising
and I think
something that we should be
concerned about.

39:58.696 --> 40:02.967 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Fake news has
been around
as long as the Internet.

40:03.001 --> 40:04.636 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What's the difference now?

40:04.669 --> 40:07.772 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CRAIG SILVERMAN: I would argue,
actually,
fake news predates the Internet
as well.

40:07.805 --> 40:12.110 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you think about the early
newspapers, they
were often partisan newspapers
and they would

40:12.143 --> 40:13.945 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
publish things that were fake.

40:13.978 --> 40:16.948 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Internet came along, and
obviously anybody
can become a publisher.

40:16.981 --> 40:18.283 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It becomes more democratized.

40:18.316 --> 40:20.652 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so, yes, you will have more
fake news.

40:20.685 --> 40:24.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But a really deciding factor is
Facebook,
where there are more than 1.7
billion people

40:24.689 --> 40:28.826 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
around the world logging in
every month, where
stuff can really get a
tremendous velocity

40:28.860 --> 40:31.362 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
very quickly and reach a huge
amount of people.

40:31.396 --> 40:33.197 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's a really game-changing
factor.

40:33.231 --> 40:36.968 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We haven't seen fake news and
hoaxes get as
much exposure as they do now,
just because

40:37.001 --> 40:39.304 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of how big a platform Facebook
is.

40:39.337 --> 40:45.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Is there a
diminishing value
of what the source is for facts
today?

40:45.376 --> 40:48.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Because it seems, when I ask
someone, where
did you hear that, they say, oh,
I saw it

40:49.013 --> 40:50.248 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on my phone.

40:50.281 --> 40:52.317 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And if I press one further, they
say, oh,
it was on Facebook.

40:52.350 --> 40:56.020 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But they often don't say, well,
it was from
BuzzFeed, and Craig Silverman
wrote it.

40:56.054 --> 41:00.224 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CRAIG SILVERMAN: I think there
is a different
pattern of information
consumption now.

41:00.258 --> 41:04.962 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
People sometimes talk about the
promiscuity
of consumers now, where, sure,
you might see

41:04.996 --> 41:06.898 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
something that a friend has
shared on Facebook.

41:06.931 --> 41:09.901 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You might see something as a
link on Twitter.

41:09.934 --> 41:11.803 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Somebody might e-mail something
to you.

41:11.836 --> 41:15.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And while you may go to your
chosen sources
in the morning or at night,
you're also getting

41:15.873 --> 41:17.608 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
stuff from other sources.

41:17.642 --> 41:21.412 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I do think, for certain
people, they don't
necessarily take a step back and
say, OK,

41:21.446 --> 41:23.281 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
where did this come from, what
is this Web
site?

41:23.314 --> 41:27.552 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We just sort of consume things
in an almost
passive way, and fake stuff can
slip into

41:27.585 --> 41:29.620 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that real stream of news a lot
easier.

41:29.654 --> 41:32.123 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Does this
create an echo
chamber?

41:32.156 --> 41:37.095 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Wall Street Journal had a
red feed/blue
feed experiment, where who had
friends that

41:37.128 --> 41:41.199 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were perhaps on one side of the
aisle saw
news that was very similar and
self-affirming.

41:41.232 --> 41:45.803 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CRAIG SILVERMAN: There is
definitely an echo
chamber effect.

41:45.837 --> 41:47.939 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Some people call it a filter
bubble.

41:47.972 --> 41:52.076 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The reality is, humans do like
to consume
information that aligns with
their existing

41:52.110 --> 41:53.878 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
beliefs.

41:53.911 --> 41:55.646 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, when we read something that
goes along
with what we already think or
that we think

41:55.680 --> 41:58.015 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
might be true, we are inclined
to believe
it.

41:58.049 --> 42:00.184 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We might also be inclined to
share it.

42:00.218 --> 42:04.722 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what happens is, on a place
like Facebook,
where there are algorithms that
are deciding

42:04.756 --> 42:08.726 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what things to show us in news
feeds, the
more that we consume a certain
type of information,

42:08.760 --> 42:12.029 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the more the algorithms learn
that we like
that, and will serve us more of
that.

42:12.063 --> 42:13.831 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Yes.

42:13.865 --> 42:15.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CRAIG SILVERMAN: And so it's
very easy for
us to end up only consuming
information from

42:15.633 --> 42:19.670 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
one point of view, only
consuming information
from a certain slice of sources.

42:19.704 --> 42:24.375 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I worry about sort of the
collapse of
that middle ground for not only
political

42:24.409 --> 42:25.943 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
conversation, but for other
things as well.

42:25.977 --> 42:28.446 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And, finally,
what's Facebook,
what's Google doing about this?

42:28.479 --> 42:32.683 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CRAIG SILVERMAN: Right now, the
main thing
that's happened is, Google --
and then Facebook

42:32.717 --> 42:36.421 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
followed suit -- have both
announced that
they will not allow fake news
sites, sites

42:36.454 --> 42:40.491 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that are publishing false
information, to
participate in their advertising
programs.

42:40.525 --> 42:44.495 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, the Google announcement is
probably a
little more significant, because
its advertising

42:44.529 --> 42:48.399 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
program was used by a lot of
sites to earn
money.

42:48.433 --> 42:52.136 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, right now, what we have
is a little
bit of shutting off of the
financial motive

42:52.170 --> 42:54.639 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for this, which I think is
actually a pretty
powerful thing.

42:54.672 --> 43:01.412 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Craig Silverman
from BuzzFeed joining us
tonight, thank you.

43:01.446 --> 43:05.850 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
CRAIG SILVERMAN: Thanks.

43:05.883 --> 43:14.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now we go from
fake news on
social streams to the TV screen,
humor, politics,

43:14.826 --> 43:18.196 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and the life of a perpetual
outsider.

43:18.229 --> 43:23.134 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown talks with the
host of the late-night
"Daily Show," Trevor Noah, whose
new memoir

43:23.167 --> 43:26.270 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
has just been published.

43:26.304 --> 43:34.512 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: It was the
morning after the
morning after, and, along with
the rest of

43:34.545 --> 43:40.618 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
us, the producers and writers of
"The Daily
Show" were grappling with the
recent earthquake

43:40.651 --> 43:42.053 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in American politics.

43:42.086 --> 43:45.156 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There were serious exchanges
about the role
of protest.

43:45.189 --> 43:47.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TREVOR NOAH, Host, "The Daily
Show": If it
were Trump people who were in
the streets

43:47.992 --> 43:52.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
doing the same thing, burning
effigies of
Hillary Clinton, it's like, come
on, guys,

43:52.630 --> 43:56.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
really, in America, in
democracy?

43:56.133 --> 43:57.401 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: There were jokes
and laughter.

43:57.435 --> 44:00.238 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: One guy had this huge sign
that was like,
"I'm Just Sad."

44:00.271 --> 44:03.074 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I was like, that's really what
it all is.

44:03.107 --> 44:04.575 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

44:04.609 --> 44:07.678 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Leading the
discussion was
the program's host, Trevor Noah.

44:07.712 --> 44:11.649 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TREVOR NOAH: That's where, as a
South African,
we share the same value in terms
of, the whole

44:11.682 --> 44:16.020 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
point of democracy is that we
don't fight
about the decision.

44:16.053 --> 44:22.260 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a scary time, but I think
we have to
be careful to not brand either
side in any

44:22.293 --> 44:24.462 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
discussion as a monolith.

44:24.495 --> 44:25.997 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's a lot more nuanced than it
seems.

44:26.030 --> 44:29.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And a lot of the time, as
people, we're not
good at dealing with nuance.

44:29.534 --> 44:32.036 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's easier to say black and
white, right
and wrong.

44:32.069 --> 44:35.039 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Out with the old,
and in with
the new.

44:35.072 --> 44:37.675 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TREVOR NOAH: Do you realize
there are so many
things we don't know?

44:37.708 --> 44:40.478 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We don't even know what the J.
in Donald J.
Trump stands for.

44:40.511 --> 44:42.113 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

44:42.146 --> 44:44.682 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TREVOR NOAH: A lot of people
don't know this,
but it actually stands for
Jesus.

44:44.715 --> 44:45.683 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

44:45.716 --> 44:47.518 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

44:47.552 --> 44:51.289 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: And the
32-year-old Noah is
still the new guy here, taking
over last year

44:51.322 --> 44:52.290 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
as the surprise pick...

44:52.323 --> 44:54.125 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
TREVOR NOAH: I am a terrible
employee.

44:54.158 --> 44:59.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: ... to replace
Jon Stewart,
who after 16 years at the helm
was a national

44:59.096 --> 45:00.197 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
cultural figure.

45:00.231 --> 45:01.499 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TREVOR NOAH: I was surprised
with everyone
else.

45:01.532 --> 45:02.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

45:02.567 --> 45:04.068 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
TREVOR NOAH: It's not like I
wasn't surprised.

45:04.101 --> 45:05.870 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I was also like, wow, who is
that guy?

45:05.903 --> 45:06.871 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That is insane.

45:06.904 --> 45:08.606 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Who is that guy?

45:08.639 --> 45:12.743 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Only an idiot would take the job
after Jon
Stewart, but, luckily, I was
that idiot.

45:12.777 --> 45:17.415 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: It hasn't been
the easiest
transition.

45:17.448 --> 45:22.653 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The late-night field has become
more crowded,
and "The Daily Show" numbers
have fallen.

45:22.687 --> 45:28.292 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But with the help of a staff of
more than
100, Noah has brought a very
particular perspective,

45:28.326 --> 45:30.728 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
one he thinks may be especially
useful now.

45:30.761 --> 45:37.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TREVOR NOAH: I come from a world
where I have
always practiced empathizing and
putting myself

45:37.635 --> 45:42.273 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in somebody else's mind, which
is very difficult
to do.

45:42.306 --> 45:48.679 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I truly believe that most
people are doing
what they believe is right from
their point

45:48.713 --> 45:50.414 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
of view.

45:50.448 --> 45:53.884 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When you think of it from
another person's
point of view and you think of
them being

45:53.918 --> 45:59.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
right from their point of view,
it then gives
you a greater insight into not
only why they

45:59.624 --> 46:04.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
think the way they do, but maybe
how to speak
to them or even how to argue
against those

46:04.462 --> 46:06.430 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
points.

46:06.464 --> 46:10.134 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Trevor Noah was
born in Johannesburg,
South Africa, in the last years
of apartheid,

46:10.167 --> 46:15.673 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
a time when a child like
himself, son of a
black South African woman and a
white Swiss

46:15.706 --> 46:20.344 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
father, was, literally, as the
title of his
new memoir puts it, born a
crime.

46:20.378 --> 46:24.181 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TREVOR NOAH: I existed in a
space where there
was no one like me most of my
life.

46:24.215 --> 46:29.020 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I never met a child who had
parents who were
different races.

46:29.053 --> 46:33.391 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I grew up either in a black
environment, or
I got to visit a white
environment.

46:33.424 --> 46:37.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Noah was raised
by his mother,
who was jailed several times for
breaking

46:37.261 --> 46:42.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
apartheid era laws, and he spent
much of his
earliest life indoors, to hide
him from a

46:42.767 --> 46:46.103 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
government that could take him
away and imprison
her.

46:46.137 --> 46:50.241 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TREVOR NOAH: I lived as an
outsider, but,
at the same time, one of the
biggest benefits

46:50.274 --> 46:54.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is, you never see yourself as
being the most
important thing, because the
world is never

46:54.478 --> 46:56.113 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
yours.

46:56.147 --> 46:58.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, what you have to do is, you
have to find
your place in other people's
worlds.

46:58.849 --> 47:00.618 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And how do you do
that?

47:00.651 --> 47:02.153 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You use this word chameleon,
right?

47:02.186 --> 47:03.220 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
TREVOR NOAH: Yes.

47:03.254 --> 47:04.689 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: That's how you
adapted.

47:04.722 --> 47:07.458 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TREVOR NOAH: That's what you do,
and you do
that by listening, you know?

47:07.491 --> 47:10.795 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Essentially, that's what a
chameleon is doing,
for all intents and purposes.

47:10.828 --> 47:13.531 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
It's listening to its
environment and adapting
accordingly.

47:13.564 --> 47:17.535 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If the chameleon's not aware of
the color
of the leaf that it's on, then
how will it

47:17.568 --> 47:19.236 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
know what color to turn to?

47:19.270 --> 47:22.940 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In the book, Noah
tells of
his mother having to act as
though she was

47:22.973 --> 47:28.412 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the black maid to her
light-skinned child,
and of his father running away
from him as

47:28.446 --> 47:29.680 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
if they were not related.

47:29.714 --> 47:31.982 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Did you realize what was
happening at the
time?

47:32.016 --> 47:32.983 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
TREVOR NOAH: No, I didn't.

47:33.017 --> 47:34.719 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And, thankfully, I didn't.

47:34.752 --> 47:39.356 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My parents were really good at
insulating
me from the reality of the world
that I was

47:39.390 --> 47:40.357 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
in.

47:40.391 --> 47:42.593 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
My dad, to me, wasn't running
away from me.

47:42.626 --> 47:44.528 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He was just running with me.

47:44.562 --> 47:47.031 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
My mom was playing.

47:47.064 --> 47:48.032 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
My dad was playing.

47:48.065 --> 47:49.734 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I was playing.

47:49.767 --> 47:51.802 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But there was a
point where
you realized that that wasn't
play.

47:51.836 --> 47:53.204 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
TREVOR NOAH: Yes.

