50:44.708 --> 50:46.710 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
He explains the humor of
cartoons.

50:46.744 --> 50:49.780 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BOB MANKOFF, Cartoon Editor,
"The New Yorker":
Every once in a while, we run a
joke that

50:49.813 --> 50:53.017 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
very few people get, and I think
that's the
hallmark of "The New Yorker."

50:53.050 --> 50:54.952 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We don't actually do it to annoy
people.

50:54.985 --> 51:01.825 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We spend an extraordinary amount
of time selecting,
going through and editing the
cartoons that

51:01.859 --> 51:04.595 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
you end up finding not funny.

51:04.628 --> 51:06.397 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

51:06.430 --> 51:15.906 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BOB MANKOFF: Part of what is
wonderful about
cartoons is, they're a little
stupid, and

51:15.940 --> 51:20.511 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
